<body>
    
    <p>Here is another example
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T114141-0500"?>in
            which<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T114139-0500" content="where"?>
            we’ll use a probability distribution that is associated with a random variable of
            interest to find probabilities. What will be new in this example is the use of
            conditional probabilities.</p>
<!--  <p>In most situations, the probability distribution is simply provided for us, as in the next example. We may assume that the probabilities have been established according to the principle of relative frequency, for instance, 
    to find the probability of a production line producing zero defective parts in an hour's time, one would record what proportion of hours, 
    in the long run, resulted in no defective parts.</p>-->
<example><title>Xavier's Production Line</title>

<p>The number of defective parts produced each hour by Xavier's production line is a random variable X with the following probability distribution:</p>
<image style="block" src="../webcontent/image012.gif" alt="A probability distribution table with two rows, labeled &quot;X&quot;
and &quot;P(X=x).&quot; The data in columns (X: P(X=x)):
        0: .15;
        1: .30;
        2: .25;
        3: .20;
        4: .10;"/>
<p>Using the probability distribution of a random variable, we can answer some probability questions:</p>
<p>(a) What is the probability of at least 2 defects in a randomly chosen hour? </p>
<p>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mi>P</m:mi>
<m:mo>(</m:mo>
<m:mi>X</m:mi>
<m:mo>≥</m:mo>
<m:mn>2</m:mn>
<m:mo>)</m:mo>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mi>P</m:mi>
<m:mo>(</m:mo>
<m:mi>X</m:mi>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mn>2</m:mn>
<m:mo>)</m:mo>
<m:mo>+</m:mo>
<m:mi>P</m:mi>
<m:mo>(</m:mo>
<m:mi>X</m:mi>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mn>3</m:mn>
<m:mo>)</m:mo>
<m:mo>+</m:mo>
<m:mi>P</m:mi>
<m:mo>(</m:mo>
<m:mi>X</m:mi>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mn>4</m:mn>
<m:mo>)</m:mo>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mn>0</m:mn>
<m:mo>.</m:mo>
<m:mn>2</m:mn>
<m:mn>5</m:mn>
<m:mo>+</m:mo>
<m:mn>0</m:mn>
<m:mo>.</m:mo>
<m:mn>2</m:mn>
<m:mn>0</m:mn>
<m:mo>+</m:mo>
<m:mn>0</m:mn>
<m:mo>.</m:mo>
<m:mn>1</m:mn>
<m:mn>0</m:mn>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mn>0</m:mn>
<m:mo>.</m:mo>
<m:mn>5</m:mn>
<m:mn>5</m:mn>
</m:math>
</p>
<p><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T114248-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T114247-0500" content="["?>Note
                that the addition principle has been
                applied.<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T114252-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T114252-0500" content="]"?></p>
    <p></p><p>(b) Suppose it is known that more than 2 defects were produced in a particular hour. What is the probability that the number of defects was fewer than 4?</p>
<p>We use the conditional probabilities definition<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mi>P</m:mi>
<m:mo>(</m:mo>
<m:mi>B</m:mi>
    <m:mo>&#160; | &#160; </m:mo>
<m:mi>A</m:mi>
<m:mo>)</m:mo>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mi>P</m:mi>
<m:mo>(</m:mo>
<m:mi>A</m:mi>
<m:mi/>
<m:mi>a</m:mi>
<m:mi>n</m:mi>
<m:mi>d</m:mi>
<m:mi/>
<m:mi>B</m:mi>
<m:mo>)</m:mo>
</m:mrow>
<m:mrow>
<m:mi>P</m:mi>
<m:mo>(</m:mo>
<m:mi>A</m:mi>
<m:mo>)</m:mo>
</m:mrow>
</m:mfrac>
</m:math> to solve:</p>
<p>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mi>P</m:mi>
<m:mo>(</m:mo>
